      {
        "number": 2,
        "title": "Five stations, one virtue — conduct that adorns the doctrine",
        "range": "2:2-10",
        "excerpt": "Older men are to be temperate, dignified, sensible, sound in faith, in love, in perseverance… so that they will adorn the doctrine of God our Savior in every respect.",
        "body": "Paul now stratifies. Five household categories receive distinct instruction: older men (2:2), older women (2:3), young women (2:4-5), young men (2:6, with Titus as model in 2:7-8), and slaves (2:9-10). The stratification matters. Pastoral realism understood that older men's besetting sins are not young women's, and that the apologetic angle of a slave's life differs from that of an elder's. Paul refuses generic spirituality.\n\n**Older men (2:2)** receive six attributes: temperate (*nephaleos*, sober), dignified (*semnos*, gravely serious), sensible (*sophron*, self-controlled), and 'sound in faith, in love, in perseverance.' The last triad echoes 1 Corinthians 13:13 (faith, hope, love) but substitutes endurance for hope — Paul wants the seasoned virtue of believers who have weathered decades. Older men exemplify what a long obedience looks like.\n\n**Older women (2:3-4)** must escape the besetting sins of their station — slander (*diabolos*, the same word used for the devil himself) and enslavement to wine — and become 'teachers of what is good' (*kalodidaskaloi*, a word possibly coined by Paul). Their primary curriculum is the discipling of younger women. The Cretan culture would not naturally produce older women who taught young women to love their husbands and children; the gospel produces exactly that.\n\n**Young women (2:4-5)** are to be trained (*sophronizo*) by the older women in seven attributes that center on the household. The list culminates with submission to their husbands 'so that the word of God will not be dishonored' (*blasphemeo* — literally *blasphemed*). The apologetic stakes are explicit. A young Christian wife whose household life contradicts the gospel becomes ammunition against the gospel itself.\n\n**Young men (2:6)** receive only one word: be sensible (*sophroneo*). The cardinal virtue of the chapter is named for a station whose besetting sin is impulse, appetite, and self-direction. Paul gives no list because the one virtue, rightly applied, governs everything else in that station.\n\n**Titus himself (2:7-8)** is to be the visible exemplar — 'an example of good deeds, with purity in doctrine, dignified, sound in speech which is beyond reproach.' He is young (Galatians 2:1, 3); the temptation to soften under cultural pressure or older-male skepticism is real. Paul commands him to embody what he preaches.\n\n**Slaves (2:9-10)** receive the chapter's most exalted theological tether. Their conduct — submitting, well-pleasing, not argumentative, not pilfering — has the purpose that 'they will adorn the doctrine of God our Savior in every respect.' The Greek verb *kosmeo* (root of *kosmos*, 'cosmetics') means to put jewelry on, to beautify. The slave at the bottom of the empire's social hierarchy adorns the doctrine of God Himself by daily trustworthiness. There is no station too low for gospel adornment.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Sophron* and its cognates (*sophroneo*, *sophronizo*, *sophronos*) saturate this chapter — five occurrences across the five stations and into 2:12. Greek moral philosophy made *sophrosune* one of the four cardinal virtues; Paul makes it a virtue *taught by grace itself*. *Kosmeo* (adorn) at 2:10 is the same verb used of brides preparing themselves in Revelation 21:2. *Diabolos* (2:3) is normally translated 'devil' — slander is devilish at root, and 'slanderer' shares its identity."
      },
      {
        "number": 3,
        "title": "The grace that has appeared and instructs",
        "range": "2:11-12",
        "excerpt": "For the grace of God has appeared, bringing salvation to all men, instructing us to deny ungodliness and worldly desires and to live sensibly, righteously and godly in the present age.",
        "body": "Verse 11 begins with *gar* — *for*. Everything that has been commanded in 2:2-10 now receives its grounding. This is the chapter's logical engine. Paul refuses to let ethics stand alone; they must be tethered to indicative reality. The reality is this: *the grace of God has appeared*.\n\n*Epephane* (has appeared) is aorist — a punctiliar past event. Paul refers to the historical complex of incarnation, cross, and resurrection. Grace is not an attitude God has always had in some abstract way; grace has *manifested itself* in a person at a moment in history. The verb is loaded — *epiphaneia* was the technical word in the Hellenistic world for the visible manifestation of a deity or the arrival of a Caesar in a city. Paul borrows the political-religious vocabulary and applies it to Christ: the true epiphany was not Caesar's; it was the carpenter from Nazareth.\n\nThe scope is universal: 'bringing salvation to *all men*.' Some have read this as universalism; the better reading is that Paul means *all kinds of men* — every station from emperor to slave, every ethnicity, every age — exactly the categories he just listed in 2:2-10. Grace does not respect Cretan social hierarchies; it appears for all of them.\n\nThen the chapter's most pastorally crucial claim: grace is *instructing us* (*paideuousa*, present participle). The verb *paideuo* is the formation of a child — discipline, correction, training. It is what the Father does to His sons in Hebrews 12:5-11. Paul says *grace itself* does this. Grace is not merely the doorway through which we entered the Christian life; grace is the schoolmaster who teaches us how to walk in it. This is the chapter's most counter-intuitive theological move. The modern dichotomy that pits grace against discipline is not Pauline. Grace *is* the trainer.\n\nThe training has two halves. Negative: 'to deny (*arneomai*) ungodliness and worldly desires.' Positive: 'to live sensibly (*sophronos*), righteously (*dikaios*), and godly (*eusebos*) in the present age.' The three positive adverbs cover the bandwidth of right living — *sophronos* toward oneself (self-control), *dikaios* toward others (justice), *eusebos* toward God (piety). Grace teaches us to say *no* and to say *yes*, and it teaches us to do both *in the present age* — not in some retreat from culture but in the middle of Crete.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Epephane* (has appeared, 2:11) and *epiphaneia* (appearing, 2:13) share the root *epiphaneo*. The Hellenistic political vocabulary of imperial manifestation is deliberately borrowed and rebaptized. *Paideuo* (instruct, train) is the Septuagint's word for the Father's discipline (Proverbs 3:11-12, quoted in Hebrews 12:5-6). *Arneomai* (deny) is the same word used of Peter denying Christ — to say *no* with force. The three adverbs *sophronos*, *dikaios*, *eusebos* form a triad of self-, neighbor-, and God-directed righteousness."
      },
      {
        "number": 4,
        "title": "The blessed hope and the great God who gave Himself",
        "range": "2:13-14",
        "excerpt": "Looking for the blessed hope and the appearing of the glory of our great God and Savior, Christ Jesus, who gave Himself for us to redeem us from every lawless deed, and to purify for Himself a people for His own possession, zealous for good deeds.",
        "body": "Verse 13 introduces the second epiphany. The first appeared in 2:11 (grace, in the incarnation); the second is *being awaited* now — 'the appearing of the glory of our great God and Savior, Christ Jesus.' The believer's life is bracketed by two manifestations. Behind us, the cross; before us, the *parousia*. Between them, grace trains us.\n\nThe Christological claim of 2:13 is one of the New Testament's clearest. The Greek construction — *tou megalou theou kai soteros hemon Iesou Christou* — falls under the Granville Sharp rule: when two singular, non-proper personal nouns are joined by *kai* with one article governing both, they refer to the same person. 'Our great God and Savior' is *one person*: Jesus Christ. He is called God outright. Calvin saw it; Murray Harris's monograph (*Jesus as God*, 1992) defends it exhaustively. Conservative scholarship across Reformed and broader evangelical lines reads it the same way. Cretan culture had its imperial cult; Paul reminds Titus's congregations who actually is *megas theos*.\n\nVerse 14 then narrates the cross itself in two purposes, joined by *kai* — '*to redeem* us from every lawless deed' AND '*to purify* for Himself a people for His own possession, zealous for good deeds.' Both purposes are essential. Most evangelical preaching emphasizes only the first — redemption, the legal cancellation of sin. Paul refuses to stop there. The cross also had a positive purpose: *to purify* (*katharizo*, ritual-purification language from Leviticus) and *to take possession* (*periousios*, exactly the Septuagint word for Israel as God's 'special possession' in Exodus 19:5 and Deuteronomy 14:2).\n\nThe cross creates a *people* — not merely individual pardoned souls, but a corporate body marked by belonging to Him. And this people is described by a striking adjective: *zelotes kalon ergon*, zealots for good deeds. The word *zelotes* was politically charged in the first century — the Jewish Zealots were the violent revolutionaries who would soon trigger the Jewish-Roman war. Paul appropriates the word and redirects it. The redeemed are zealots not for armed revolt but for *kala erga*, beautiful works. The cross did not produce passive recipients; it produced people on fire for visible goodness.\n\nThis is the chapter's deepest counter to two errors. Against legalism: every command in 2:2-10 stands because Christ has *already* redeemed and purified — the conduct flows from accomplished work, not toward it. Against antinomianism: the cross had two purposes, not one, and the second was *purification of a people zealous for good deeds*. Anyone who claims the cross while remaining indifferent to good deeds has missed half of what the cross was for.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Tou megalou theou kai soteros hemon Iesou Christou* (2:13) — Granville Sharp construction; 'our great God and Savior' is one person, Jesus Christ. *Lutroo* (redeem, 2:14) is the verb of ransom-payment, echoing Psalm 130:8 (the Septuagint of 'He will redeem Israel from all his iniquities'). *Periousios* (His own possession) is the Septuagint adjective for Israel's covenant identity in Exodus 19:5 — Paul transfers Israel's covenant vocabulary to the church. *Zelotes kalon ergon* — zealots of beautiful works."
      },
      {
        "number": 5,
        "title": "Speak, exhort, reprove with all authority",
        "range": "2:15",
        "excerpt": "These things speak and exhort and reprove with all authority. Let no one disregard you.",
        "body": "The chapter closes with a three-fold imperative addressed to Titus. *Speak* (*laleo*) — the basic verb of communication, gather the previous fourteen verses and say them. *Exhort* (*parakaleo*) — call alongside, encourage, urge with the warmth that wants the listener's good. *Reprove* (*elegcho*) — convict, expose, correct with authority that names sin as sin. Paul refuses to let pastoral ministry be reduced to any one tone. Some material requires teaching; some requires encouragement; some requires correction. Titus must do all three.\n\nThe phrase 'with all authority' (*meta pases epitages*) is striking. *Epitage* is a strong word — command, injunction, the authority of one who can require compliance. It is the same root that gives military 'orders.' Titus is not a suggestion-maker. He stands under apostolic commission, and apostolic commission carries weight. The Cretan congregations may not feel like obeying — but Titus is to speak in such a way that disregard is the listener's problem, not his weakness.\n\n'Let no one disregard you' (*medeis sou periphroneito*) closes the chapter with a defensive imperative. *Periphroneo* means to think around, to look past, to dismiss. Titus is young (Galatians 2 timing suggests perhaps in his thirties); Cretan culture and older elders alike could be tempted to dismiss him. Paul commands the opposite. The grounds of Titus's authority are not his age, his education, or his Cretan citizenship — he had none. The grounds are the apostolic *epitage* he carries. The chapter ends as it began — with Titus's voice, set against the silenced mouths of 1:11, speaking the things that fit sound doctrine.\n\nRead canonically, 2:15 is the warrant for every faithful pastor's confidence. A man preaching what Scripture preaches stands under the same authority Titus stood under. His listeners' disregard, when it comes, falls not on him but on the apostolic word he speaks. The verse also forecloses one common pastoral error — softening the message because of audience reaction. Paul commands authoritative speech in three modes (speak, exhort, reprove); he does not authorize any mode that omits authority.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Parakaleo* (exhort) and *elegcho* (reprove) are paired again in 2 Timothy 4:2 — 'reprove, rebuke, exhort, with great patience and instruction.' Together they cover the warm and the corrective poles of pastoral speech. *Epitage* (authority, 2:15) is used of imperial decrees in Hellenistic papyri; Paul applies it to apostolic commission. *Periphroneo* (disregard) is built on *peri-* (around) + *phroneo* (think) — to think around someone, to look past them."
      }
